Exploring the Relationship Between Financial Statement Items and Stock Performance

Patrick Johnson and Anh Pham

Project Goals

The goal of this project is to analyze and determine how different financial statement indexes correlate with stock price changes for companies in the S&P 500 over the past ten years. Instead of focusing on the most common measure, earnings per share (EPS), we want to see if factors like depreciation, assets, or liabilities also help explain stock performance. By finding these correlations, we hope to better understand how financial decisions and company internal set up are reflected in investor behavior and market value.

Project Dataset

The datasets we are considering working with are the SEC EDGAR Financial Statement Metrics and Yahoo Finance Historical Stock Data. Together, these two datasets will allow us to examine how companies internal financial structures influence their external market performance over time. Our goal is to identify relationships between balance sheet and income statement items, especially those unrelated to earnings per share (EPS) (such as depreciation and total liabilities), and stock price trends for firms in the S&P 500 index.

The SEC EDGAR dataset provides standardized financial statement information of publicly traded U.S. companies, including variables like total assets, total liabilities, depreciation, and operating income. The Yahoo Finance dataset contains corresponding market data such as daily closing prices and trading volumes. By organizing the stock data by year and linking it to the financial data from EDGAR using company tickers or IDs, we can create one dataset that shows both a companys financial performance and its market value

This integration will allow us to answer questions such as: How do changes in liabilities or depreciation expenses relate to changes in stock prices? Do firms with more asset growth correlate to higher long-term stock performance? Combining these two datasets bridges the gap between corporate accounting and investor behavior, providing a comprehensive foundation for analyzing how internal financial indicators translate into market outcomes.

Glossary

  • CIK (Central Index Key): A unique 10-digit identifier assigned by the SEC to every entity that files with EDGAR, including public companies, mutual funds, and individuals. Used to look up filings in SEC APIs and EDGAR.

  • start: The beginning date of the reporting period for the reported XBRL fact. Used for facts that cover a period (e.g., revenue for a quarter or year). Example: "start": "2024-01-01"

  • end: The ending date of the reporting period for the fact. This, combined with start, defines the timeframe for period-based financial metrics.Example: "end": "2024-09-30"

  • val: The numeric value of the XBRL-reported fact (e.g., revenue, assets, operating income). Usually appears as a raw number without formatting. Example: "val": 73582000000 (which is 73.582B)

  • accn (Accession Number): A unique EDGAR-generated ID for the specific filing containing this fact. You can use it to locate the filings directory and document list. Example: "accn": "0001652044-24-000118"

  • fy (Fiscal Year): The fiscal year associated with the filing (not necessarily the calendar year). Companies with non-December year-ends may have FY differing from calendar year. Example: "fy": 2024

  • fp (Fiscal Period): The fiscal period represented by the filing. Common values include: Q1 = First fiscal quarter

  • filed: The date the filing was submitted to the SEC EDGAR system.

  • frame: A special time-period code used by XBRL for instant or duration frames.

Before we begin working with the data, we will explain the financial terms and how these elements are used in later codes. Our project focuses on analyzing companies in the S&P 500, a list of the 500 leading stock exchange companies in the U.S.

What is a Ticker? A ticker, also called a stock symbol, is a short and unique abbreviation used to identify a publicly traded company in the stock market. A company is assigned a ticker when it goes public and trades stocks the first time. For example: Apples ticker is AAPL, Googles is GOOGL, and Walmart is WMT. Tickers exist to prevent name confusion as many companies share similar names/terms.

To access financial filings, we must convert the companys ticker into a CIK number. Then use the CIK to request the financial data.

Match Each S&P 500 Ticker to Its SEC CIK Number

The SEC does not use ticker symbols to organize company filings.
Instead, every public company has a unique ID called a CIK.

In this step, we download the SECs official list that pairs each ticker with its CIK, clean it into a table, and then match these CIKs to our S&P 500 tickers.
This gives us the SEC ID number for each company so we can access their filings later.

In[129]:
import requests
import pandas as pd

# The SEC requires us to include a user-agent when making requests
headers = {
    'User-Agent': 'Your Company Name pjohnson3@tulane.edu',
    'Accept-Encoding': 'gzip, deflate'
}

# Download the SEC file that lists tickers and their CIK numbers
CIK = requests.get('https://www.sec.gov/include/ticker.txt', headers=headers)

# Turn the text file into a dictionary: {Symbol : CIK}
ticker_map = dict(line.split('\t') for line in CIK.text.upper().strip().split('\n') if line)

# Convert the dictionary into a DataFrame for easier use
ticker_map = pd.DataFrame(list(ticker_map.items()), columns=['Symbol', 'CIK'])

# Make sure all CIKs are 10 digits long (add leading zeros if needed)
ticker_map['CIK'] = ticker_map['CIK'].astype(str).str.zfill(10)

# Remove duplicate CIK numbers to keep the table clean
ticker_map = ticker_map.drop_duplicates(subset='CIK', keep='first')

# Match S&P 500 tickers with their CIK numbers
sp500_cik = pd.merge(sp500_tickers, ticker_map, on='Symbol', how='left')

# Print preview to ensure everthing works
print(sp500_cik.head())
print(f"Total symbols: {sp500_cik['Symbol'].count()}")
print(f"Unique CIKs: {sp500_cik['CIK'].nunique()}")
print(f"\nSample CIKs (should be 10 digits):")
print(sp500_cik[['Symbol', 'CIK']].head(10))

Download Financial Data (SEC) and Stock Prices (Yahoo)

We collect two types of information:

1. Financial Data from the SEC

We use the CIK to download each companys financial facts from the SECs EDGAR system (an online database where public companies submit their official financial reports). These facts include items like revenue, expenses, assets, and the reporting period.

In[101]:
# The SEC requires us to include a User-Agent so they know who is making the request
headers = {
    'User-Agent': 'Patrick Johnson pjohnson3@tulane.edu'  # Replace with your info
}

# CIK list - properly formatted with leading zeros (10 digits)
CIK_list = ['0001652044', '0000320193']  # Google (Alphabet) and Apple

# Create DataFrame to store all SEC financial data
all_edgar_df = pd.DataFrame()

# Fetch EDGAR data for each CIK
for cik in CIK_list:
    # Build the API URL for this company's financial data
    edgar_api = f'https://data.sec.gov/api/xbrl/companyfacts/CIK{cik}.json'
    edgar_response = requests.get(edgar_api, headers=headers)

    # Initialize data list for this CIK
    us_gaap_data = []

    if edgar_response.status_code == 200:
        data = edgar_response.json()

        # Extract US-GAAP facts
        if 'us-gaap' in data.get('facts', {}):
            # Loop through each financial item reported by the company
            for fact_name, fact_details in data['facts']['us-gaap'].items():
                if 'units' in fact_details:
                    for unit_type, records in fact_details['units'].items():
                        for record in records:
                            us_gaap_data.append({
                                'fact_name': fact_name,
                                'label': fact_details.get('label', ''),
                                'description': fact_details.get('description', ''),
                                'unit': unit_type,
                                'value': record.get('val'),
                                'start_date': record.get('start'),
                                'end_date': record.get('end'),
                                'filed_date': record.get('filed'),
                                'form': record.get('form'),
                                'frame': record.get('frame', ''),
                                'fiscal_year': record.get('fy'),
                                'fiscal_period': record.get('fp'),
                                'accn': record.get('accn'),
                                'company_cik': data.get('cik'),
                                'company_name': data.get('entityName')
                            })

        # Create DataFrame for this CIK
        edgar_df = pd.DataFrame(us_gaap_data)

        # Add ticker based on CIK
        edgar_df['Ticker'] = sp500_cik.loc[sp500_cik['CIK'] == cik]['Symbol'].iloc[0]

        # Add this company's data to the full EDGAR dataset
        all_edgar_df = pd.concat([all_edgar_df, edgar_df], ignore_index=True)

        print(f"Loaded {len(edgar_df)} records for CIK {cik} ({edgar_df['company_name'].iloc[0] if len(edgar_df) > 0 else 'Unknown'})")
    else:
        print(f"Error fetching CIK {cik}: Status {edgar_response.status_code}")

Cleaning the EDGAR Data

The raw EDGAR dataset contains many fields that we do not need for this project. Since our goal is to study how financial statement items relate to stock price changes, we only keep the columns that provide:

  • fact_name: the name of the financial metric
  • value: the reported value
  • start_date, end_date, filed_date: the reporting dates
  • form: the form type (10-K, 10-Q, etc.)
  • fiscal_year, fiscal_period: the fiscal year/period
  • Ticker: the company ticker

We remove metadata columns such as descriptions, internal SEC IDs, and text fields that do not contribute to numerical analysis. This makes the dataset cleaner and easier to use for correlation and price-change calculations.

Creating Lookup Tables for Stock Prices

Here we build a lookup dictionary that stores all daily prices for each ticker. We then define helper functions that find the stock price on a specific date or the first price after a filing date. These functions will be used later during parallel processing.

In[107]:
print("Creating lookup dictionary...")
yahoo_dict = {}
for ticker in yahoo_df_filtered['Ticker'].unique():
    ticker_data = yahoo_df_filtered[yahoo_df_filtered['Ticker'] == ticker].sort_values('Date')
    yahoo_dict[ticker] = ticker_data

# Helper: price at or before a given date
def get_price_at_end_date(args):
    idx, ticker, end_date = args
    if ticker not in yahoo_dict:
        return None
    data = yahoo_dict[ticker]
    match = data[data['Date'] <= end_date]
    return match.iloc[-1]['Close'] if len(match) > 0 else None

# Helper: first price after a given date
def get_price_after_filing(args):
    idx, ticker, filing_date = args
    if ticker not in yahoo_dict:
        return None
    data = yahoo_dict[ticker]
    match = data[data['Date'] > filing_date]
    return match.iloc[0]['Close'] if len(match) > 0 else None

Matching Filing Dates to Stock Prices with Parallel Processing

This step uses all available CPU cores to quickly match each SEC filing to the stock price at the quarter end date, the price right before the filing, and the price right after the filing. Using multiprocessing speeds up the process for large datasets.

In[108]:
print("Preparing data for multiprocessing...")
args_list_end = [(idx, row.Ticker, row.end_date) for idx, row in enumerate(full_data.itertuples())]
args_list_filing = [(idx, row.Ticker, row.filed_date) for idx, row in enumerate(full_data.itertuples())]

num_cores = cpu_count()
print(f"\nUsing {num_cores} cores")

print("Calculating 'Price at end date'...")
with Pool(num_cores) as pool:
    full_data['Price at end date'] = list(pool.imap(get_price_at_end_date, args_list_end, chunksize=1000))

print("Calculating 'Price before filing'...")
with Pool(num_cores) as pool:
    full_data['Price before'] = list(pool.imap(get_price_at_end_date, args_list_filing, chunksize=1000))

print("Calculating 'Price after filing'...")
with Pool(num_cores) as pool:
    full_data['Price after'] = list(pool.imap(get_price_after_filing, args_list_filing, chunksize=1000))

Calculating Price Reactions Around Quarterly Filings

Once the prices are matched, we calculate how much the stock moved after the filing, both in dollar terms and percent terms. We also measure the drift between the quarter end date and the filing date. The table below shows a sample of these calculations for the selected company.

# Price reactions around the filing
full_data['Price after % change'] = ((full_data['Price after'] / full_data['Price before']) - 1) * 100
full_data['Price after $ change'] = full_data['Price after'] - full_data['Price before']

# Price drift between quarter end and filing date
full_data['Price drift during lag %'] = ((full_data['Price before'] / full_data['Price at end date']) - 1) * 100
full_data['Price drift during lag $'] = full_data['Price before'] - full_data['Price at end date']

Explanation of Price Reaction Columns

This table above shows how the stock price changed around each quarterly SEC filing.
Here is what each column means:

  • Price at end date: The stock price on the last day of the quarter (when the financial results apply).
  • Price before: The stock price right before the company released the filing.
  • Price after: The first stock price available after the filing became public.
  • Price after % change: How much the stock moved the day after the filing (in percent).
  • Price after $ change: How much the stock moved the day after the filing (in dollars).
  • Price drift during lag %: How much the stock changed between the quarter end and the filing date.
  • Price drift during lag $: Dollar change during that same lag period.

These columns help us see two things:

  1. How the market reacted immediately to the new financial report, and
  2. How the stock moved in the weeks between the quarter end and the filing date.

We currently have more values than we need. Generally, we need 10q and 10k forms, not other forms like 8k. Let's narrow this dataset down to get rid of 8k values.

Why We Keep Only 10-K and 10-Q Filings

Companies submit different types of reports to the SEC. For this project, we only keep the filings that contain full financial statements:

  • 10-K: the annual financial report
  • 10-Q: the quarterly financial report

These two filings are filed on a regular schedule and directly show a companys financial performance, which is what we need to study how stock prices react to earnings information.

We remove 8-K filings because they report unexpected, one-off events (like mergers, lawsuits, or executive changes). They are not part of the normal reporting cycle and would add noise to our analysis.

Normalizing Financial Variables Across Reporting Periods

Before analyzing correlations, we need to make sure the financial values from EDGAR are consistent across different types of statements. Balance sheet items (such as total assets or long-term debt) report a single value each quarter, using the end date to show when the snapshot was taken.

Income statement items (such as revenue or net income) behave differently. EDGAR often reports two types of values each quarter:

  1. Quarter-over-quarter (QoQ) results for that specific quarter
  2. Year-to-date (YTD) results that accumulate all quarters so far

This means Q2 and Q3 sometimes appear twice, while Q4 may show a full-year total instead of the value for just that quarter. If we do not normalize these values, our analysis would mix different types of numbers and create misleading results.

To understand this pattern clearly, we first plot example balance sheet and income statement items over time. This will help us see where duplicates occur and how values behave across quarters, so we can correctly filter the data to keep only the QoQ entries for both statement types.

First pass is to find start and end dates that exist, and whether or not they are only 3 months worth by finding difference in days < 100. And calculating Q4 as the difference between q3 ytd and q4 ytd. Then if these quarters dont exist, we comb over the difference of ytd values. (i.e Q3 ytd - Q2 ytd = Q3)

def q_normalize(variable):
    variable = variable.copy()

    # Remove comparative data by keeping only the earliest filing for each end_date + fiscal_period
    if 'filed' in variable.columns:
        variable['filed'] = pd.to_datetime(variable['filed'])
        variable = variable.sort_values('filed')
        variable = variable.drop_duplicates(subset=['end_date', 'fiscal_period'], keep='first')

    variable_narrowed = pd.DataFrame(columns=variable.columns)

    for _, row in variable.iterrows():
        # Skip rows with missing dates
        if pd.isna(row['start_date']) or pd.isna(row['end_date']):
            continue

        start = pd.to_datetime(row['start_date'])
        end = pd.to_datetime(row['end_date'])

        # Compute days difference
        days_diff = (end - start).days

        if days_diff < 100:
            # Keep actual quarterly data (days < 100)
            variable_narrowed = pd.concat([variable_narrowed, row.to_frame().T], ignore_index=True)
        else:
            # Handle FY -> Q4 conversion (FY - Q3 YTD)
            if row['fiscal_period'] == 'FY':
                q4 = row.copy()
                q4['fiscal_period'] = 'Q4'

                # Get Q3 YTD matching rows - same end_date year
                q3_ytd_match = variable.loc[
                    (pd.to_datetime(variable['end_date']).dt.year == pd.to_datetime(row['end_date']).year) &
                    (variable['fiscal_period'] == 'Q3') &
                    ((pd.to_datetime(variable['end_date']) - pd.to_datetime(variable['start_date'])).dt.days > 100)
                ]

                # Subtract Q3 YTD value if it exists
                if not q3_ytd_match.empty:
                    q4['value'] = float(q4['value']) - float(q3_ytd_match.iloc[0]['value'])
                    variable_narrowed = pd.concat([variable_narrowed, q4.to_frame().T], ignore_index=True)

            # Handle Q2 YTD -> extract Q1 and Q2
            elif row['fiscal_period'] == 'Q2':
                # METHOD 1: Try to find actual Q2 (days < 100) - same end_date year
                q2_actual_match = variable.loc[
                    (pd.to_datetime(variable['end_date']).dt.year == pd.to_datetime(row['end_date']).year) &
                    (variable['fiscal_period'] == 'Q2') &
                    ((pd.to_datetime(variable['end_date']) - pd.to_datetime(variable['start_date'])).dt.days < 100)
                ]

                if not q2_actual_match.empty:
                    # We have actual Q2, so calculate Q1 = Q2_YTD - Q2_actual
                    q1 = row.copy()
                    q1['fiscal_period'] = 'Q1'
                    q1['value'] = float(row['value']) - float(q2_actual_match.iloc[0]['value'])
                    variable_narrowed = pd.concat([variable_narrowed, q1.to_frame().T], ignore_index=True)
                else:
                    # METHOD 2: No actual Q2 found, try Q1 YTD method
                    q1_ytd_match = variable.loc[
                        (pd.to_datetime(variable['end_date']).dt.year == pd.to_datetime(row['end_date']).year) &
                        (variable['fiscal_period'] == 'Q1') &
                        ((pd.to_datetime(variable['end_date']) - pd.to_datetime(variable['start_date'])).dt.days > 100)
                    ]

                    if not q1_ytd_match.empty:
                        # Calculate Q2 = Q2_YTD - Q1_YTD
                        q2 = row.copy()
                        q2['value'] = float(row['value']) - float(q1_ytd_match.iloc[0]['value'])
                        variable_narrowed = pd.concat([variable_narrowed, q2.to_frame().T], ignore_index=True)

                        # Also extract Q1 from Q1_YTD if it doesn't exist as actual
                        q1_actual_match = variable.loc[
                            (pd.to_datetime(variable['end_date']).dt.year == pd.to_datetime(row['end_date']).year) &
                            (variable['fiscal_period'] == 'Q1') &
                            ((pd.to_datetime(variable['end_date']) - pd.to_datetime(variable['start_date'])).dt.days < 100)
                        ]

                        if q1_actual_match.empty:
                            q1 = q1_ytd_match.iloc[0].copy()
                            variable_narrowed = pd.concat([variable_narrowed, q1.to_frame().T], ignore_index=True)

            # Handle Q3 YTD -> extract Q3
            elif row['fiscal_period'] == 'Q3':
                # METHOD 1: Try to find actual Q3 (days < 100) - same end_date year
                q3_actual_match = variable.loc[
                    (pd.to_datetime(variable['end_date']).dt.year == pd.to_datetime(row['end_date']).year) &
                    (variable['fiscal_period'] == 'Q3') &
                    ((pd.to_datetime(variable['end_date']) - pd.to_datetime(variable['start_date'])).dt.days < 100)
                ]

                if q3_actual_match.empty:
                    # METHOD 2: Calculate Q3 = Q3_YTD - Q2_YTD - same end_date year
                    q2_ytd_match = variable.loc[
                        (pd.to_datetime(variable['end_date']).dt.year == pd.to_datetime(row['end_date']).year) &
                        (variable['fiscal_period'] == 'Q2') &
                        ((pd.to_datetime(variable['end_date']) - pd.to_datetime(variable['start_date'])).dt.days > 100)
                    ]

                    if not q2_ytd_match.empty:
                        q3 = row.copy()
                        q3['value'] = float(row['value']) - float(q2_ytd_match.iloc[0]['value'])
                        variable_narrowed = pd.concat([variable_narrowed, q3.to_frame().T], ignore_index=True)

    # Sort by end_date FIRST before deduplication
    variable_narrowed = variable_narrowed.sort_values('end_date')

    # Deduplicate keeping the row with the correct fiscal_period (Q1, Q2, Q3, Q4 order)
    # For each end_date, determine the correct quarter based on the month
    variable_narrowed['end_date_dt'] = pd.to_datetime(variable_narrowed['end_date'])
    variable_narrowed['expected_quarter'] = variable_narrowed['end_date_dt'].dt.month.map({
        3: 'Q1', 6: 'Q2', 9: 'Q3', 12: 'Q4'
    })

    # Keep rows where fiscal_period matches expected_quarter, or if no match, keep first
    def select_best_row(group):
        # Try to find row matching expected quarter
        matching = group[group['fiscal_period'] == group['expected_quarter'].iloc[0]]
        if not matching.empty:
            return matching.iloc[0]
        else:
            return group.iloc[0]

    variable_narrowed = variable_narrowed.groupby('end_date', as_index=False).apply(select_best_row)
    variable_narrowed = variable_narrowed.reset_index(drop=True)

    # Drop helper columns
    variable_narrowed = variable_narrowed.drop(['end_date_dt', 'expected_quarter'], axis=1, errors='ignore')

    return variable_narrowed

income_normalized = q_normalize(income_df)

def compute_changes_with_max_gap(df, max_days=100, group_by_ticker=False, verbose=True):
    """
    Compute row-to-row percent change in 'value' ordered by 'end_date'.
    - If group_by_ticker=True, compute separately per ticker.
    - Only calculate change if previous row's end_date is within max_days.
    - Otherwise, value_%_change is NaN.
    """
    df = df.copy()
    df['end_date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['end_date'], errors='coerce')
    df['value'] = pd.to_numeric(df['value'], errors='coerce')
    df['value_%_change'] = np.nan

    if group_by_ticker and 'Ticker' in df.columns:
        for ticker in df['Ticker'].unique():
            sub = df[df['Ticker'] == ticker].sort_values('end_date').reset_index()
            for i in range(1, len(sub)):
                prev_val = sub.at[i-1, 'value']
                curr_val = sub.at[i, 'value']
                prev_date = sub.at[i-1, 'end_date']
                curr_date = sub.at[i, 'end_date']

                if pd.notna(prev_val) and pd.notna(curr_val) and pd.notna(prev_date) and pd.notna(curr_date):
                    if (curr_date - prev_date).days <= max_days:
                        df.at[sub.at[i, 'index'], 'value_%_change'] = ((curr_val - prev_val) / abs(prev_val)) * 100
    else:
        sub = df.sort_values('end_date').reset_index()
        for i in range(1, len(sub)):
            prev_val = sub.at[i-1, 'value']
            curr_val = sub.at[i, 'value']
            prev_date = sub.at[i-1, 'end_date']
            curr_date = sub.at[i, 'end_date']

            if pd.notna(prev_val) and pd.notna(curr_val) and pd.notna(prev_date) and pd.notna(curr_date):
                if (curr_date - prev_date).days <= max_days:
                    df.at[sub.at[i, 'index'], 'value_%_change'] = ((curr_val - prev_val) / abs(prev_val)) * 100

    df['value_%_change'] = df['value_%_change'].round(2)

    if verbose:
        print(f"Computed value_%_change with max {max_days} day gap. Non-NaN rows: {df['value_%_change'].notna().sum()}")

    return df

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot_correlation(a, example):

  # Define variables
  y1_label = a
  y2 = 'value_%_change'
  y3 = 'Price after % change'
  FILTER_TICKER = 'GOOGL'

  df = example.copy()

  if 'end_date' not in df.columns:
      raise KeyError("DataFrame must have an 'end_date' column to derive actual reported quarters.")

  df['end_date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['end_date'], errors='coerce')

  df['reported_quarter'] = df['end_date'].dt.to_period('Q')

  df['quarter_end'] = df['reported_quarter'].dt.to_timestamp(how='end')

  plot_data = df[(df['Ticker'] == FILTER_TICKER) & (df['label'] == y1_label)].copy()

  plot_data = plot_data.dropna(subset=[y2, y3, 'quarter_end'])

  plot_data['__q_ordinal'] = plot_data['reported_quarter'].apply(lambda p: p.ordinal)
  plot_data = plot_data.sort_values('__q_ordinal').reset_index(drop=True)

  correlation = plot_data[[y2, y3]].corr().iloc[0, 1]
  print(f"\nCorrelation between {y2} and {y3} for {FILTER_TICKER}: {correlation:.4f}")

  fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 8))

  ax.plot(plot_data['quarter_end'], plot_data[y2], marker='o', linewidth=2, markersize=6, label=f'{a} % Change')
  ax.plot(plot_data['quarter_end'], plot_data[y3], marker='^', linewidth=2, markersize=6, label='Price % Change')

  ax.axhline(y=0, color='red', linestyle='--', alpha=0.5, linewidth=1)

  ax.set_xlabel('Quarter End (reported)', fontsize=12)
  ax.set_ylabel('Normalized Percentage Change (%)', fontsize=12)
  ax.set_title(f'Normalized Quarter-over-Quarter Changes: {y1_label} vs. Stock Price\nTicker: {FILTER_TICKER}\nCorrelation: {correlation:.4f}', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', pad=14)

  ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
  ax.legend(loc='best', fontsize=10)
  if plot_data.empty:
    print("No data after filtering. Nothing to plot.")
    print("Ticker filter:", FILTER_TICKER)
    print("Label filter:", y1_label)
    print("Available labels:", df['label'].unique())
    print("Available tickers:", df['Ticker'].unique())
    return

  x_labels = [str(p) for p in plot_data['reported_quarter']]
  ax.set_xticks(plot_data['quarter_end'])
  ax.set_xticklabels(x_labels, rotation=45, ha='right')

  # Adjust layout and display
  fig.tight_layout()
  plt.show()

Modeling Plan: Predicting Stock Price Reaction After Financial Filings

Our goal is to build a model that predicts how much a stock will move right after a company files its quarterly or annual report with the SEC.

Dependent Variable: Price after % change
This is the percentage change in the stock price from just before the filing to the first trading day after the filing. It represents the markets immediate reaction to the new financial information.

Independent Variables:

  1. Quarter-over-quarter earnings growth (value_%_change)
    Measures how much a financial item (such as revenue or earnings) changed compared to the previous quarter.

  2. Price drift during the filing lag (%)
    Shows how the stock moved between the quarter end and the actual filing date. This captures market expectations before the report is released.

  3. Previous quarter stock price (Price at end date)
    Gives a baseline level of the stock price before any new information.

Modeling Approach

We will use a regression model (such as Linear Regression or Random Forest Regression) to predict the size of the stock price reaction. The dataset will be split into training and testing sets so we can measure how well the model performs on new, unseen data.

We will evaluate the model using:

  • R^2 how much of the variation in price reaction the model can explain
  • RMSE how far predictions are from the actual values on average

Our exploratory graphs show that changes in financial performance often move in the same direction as stock price reactions. Because the data shows these relationships visually, using earnings metrics and price drift as predictors is a reasonable way to model how investors respond to new filings.
